WEBVTT

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.000
NARRATOR: THE GLOBALIZATION
 OF THE WORLD'S ECONOMY

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:25.000
HAS BROUGHT WITH IT
 THE LARGEST MOVEMENT OF PEOPLE

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
IN THE HISTORY
 OF MODERN TIMES.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
EVERYWHERE,
 MILLIONS OF PEOPLE

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:31.000
ARE ON THEIR WAY
 TO SOMEWHERE NEW.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
NO WALL OR BARRIER IS
 STRONG ENOUGH TO STOP MIGRANTS

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.000
AS THEY CROSS
 INTERNATIONAL BORDERS,

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
ON A JOURNEY
 TO WHERE THE ACTION IS--

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
THE GLOBAL CITIES.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
[BAND PLAYING
 THE DOORS' "BREAK ON THROUGH"]

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
NARRATOR: TOKYO IS A GLOBAL
 CITY OF POWER AND FRENZY.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
* BREAK ON THROUGH
TO THE OTHER SIDE...

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
NARRATOR:
 TOKYO BUZZES WITH ENERGY.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.000
TRAINS RUMBLE
 THROUGH THE NIGHT.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.000
* OH, YEAH!

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
DOWN EVERY STREET,
 HUGE CROWDS FIGHT FOR SPACE,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
WITH CARS
 RUSHING BY AT ALL HOURS.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
EVEN THOUGH TOKYO
 OUTWARDLY SEEMS WESTERNIZED,

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
UNLIKE WESTERN
 GLOBAL CITIES, TOKYO REMAINS

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
A CITY WITHOUT
 A VISIBLE FOREIGN POPULATION.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
JONATHAN WATTS: IF YOU LOOK
 AT THE COUNTRY AS A WHOLE,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
I THINK IT'S ONE PERCENT,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.000
OR MAYBE EVEN LESS THAN
 ONE PERCENT

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
OF THE POPULATION
 ARE NON-JAPANESE.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
SO YOU'VE GOT THIS INCREDIBLY
HOMOGENOUS NATION.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.000
AND I THINK THAT'S DEFINITELY
A RESULT OF GOVERNMENT POLICY--

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.000
VERY, VERY TIGHT
IMMIGRATION RULES.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
NARRATOR: PERHAPS
 THE MOST VISIBLE

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.000
FOREIGN PRESENCE IN TOKYO
 ARE THE THOUSANDS OF WOMEN

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.000
WHO COME
 FROM ALL OVER THE WORLD

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
TO PROVIDE ENTERTAINMENT
 TO JAPANESE MEN.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
THE GOVERNMENT HAS DECIDED
 TO DISCOURAGE THIS TRADE,

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
NOT WITH PROHIBITION,
 BUT WITH REGULATIONS.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
ONE SUCH REGULATION STATES
 THAT EACH FOREIGN ENTERTAINER

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
MUST PASS A TEST
 OF DANCING SKILLS

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
SHE WILL HARDLY NEED.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
IMMIGRATION HAS NOT SO FAR
 CAUSED AS MUCH CONCERN IN JAPAN

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.000
AS IN OTHER
 DEVELOPED COUNTRIES.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
HOWEVER, IT'S ONLY
 A MATTER OF TIME

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
BEFORE JAPAN IS FACED WITH
 SOCIAL AND POLITICAL STRAINS

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
OVER THE ISSUE OF IMMIGRATION.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
HISTORICALLY, JAPAN
HASN'T DEALT WITH IMMIGRATION,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
HASN'T BROUGHT IN
LARGE NUMBERS OF PEOPLE.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
AND A LOT OF JAPANESE
HAVEN'T HAD CONTACT

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
WITH THE OUTSIDE WORLD
 AND WITH OTHER PEOPLE.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
AND SO IT MAY NOT BE
THE EASIEST PLACE

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
FOR FOREIGNERS TO COME.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
[MAN TRANSLATING RYO ONOYAMA]

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.000
JAPAN IS NOT YET READY

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
TO ACCEPT OUTSIDERS.
 WE'RE STILL A CLOSED COUNTRY.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
WE STILL HAVE
 NOTIONS OF RACIAL PURITY.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
THIS IS WHY I DO THINK
 JAPANESE SOCIETY IS RACIST.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
HERE IN TOKYO, THERE'S RACISM
 IN EVERYDAY LIFE,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
AND STRONG FEELINGS
 OF REJECTION TOWARD FOREIGNERS.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
FOR INSTANCE,
 THERE ARE MANY CASES

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:00.000
OF FOREIGNERS
 BEING DENIED ENTRANCE

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:01.000
TO PUBLIC BATHS
 AND RESTAURANTS.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
I THINK
THE REASON IS RACISM.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
I THINK THAT JAPAN BELIEVES

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.000
THAT THE BEST WAY FOR IT TO HAVE
A SOCIALLY STABLE COUNTRY

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
IS TO HAVE A COUNTRY
 WITH AS FEW

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
FOREIGN IMMIGRANTS AS POSSIBLE.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
[MAN TRANSLATING ONOYAMA] IN
 ANOTHER CASE OF BLATANT RACISM,

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.000
TWO BRAZILIAN IMMIGRANTS
 WERE MURDERED BY A YOUTH GANG,

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
SIMPLY BECAUSE THESE JAPANESE
 YOUNGSTERS BELIEVED

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
BRAZILIANS DON'T BELONG HERE,
 AND SHOULD GO BACK HOME.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:38.000
NARRATOR:
 ACCORDING TO A RECENT POLL,

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:40.000
ABOUT 80% OF JAPANESE

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.000
ARE AGAINST
 ACCEPTING MORE FOREIGNERS.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
BUT JAPAN'S
 RAPIDLY AGEING SOCIETY

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
AND RECORD LOW BIRTHRATE

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
ARE FORCING JAPANESE TO RECKON
 WITH AN INDISPUTABLE FACT--

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
THAT THEIR COUNTRY MUST ACCEPT

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
MORE IMMIGRANTS
 INTO ITS WORKFORCE.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.000
KANAK: YEAH, I DON'T THINK
 IT'S GONNA BE A GREAT INFLUX.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.000
I DON'T THINK
YOU'RE GONNA SEE THEM

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.000
FLING THE DOORS OPEN
TO IMMIGRATION.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
BUT I THINK YOU'RE GONNA SEE
A STEADY, STEADY INCREASE.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
HARALD EISENACH:
 ALL OUR STAFF HERE IN JAPAN--

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
WE CERTAINLY STILL HAVE
 THE MAJORITY OF THE PEOPLE

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:14.000
JAPANESE, BEING JAPANESE.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
WE HAVE 80%,
 81% OF OUR STAFF,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
WHICH IS ROUGHLY
1,400 PEOPLE, AS JAPANESE.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
BUT THE REMAINING 20 PERCENT

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
CONSISTS ALL
OF 29 DIFFERENT NATIONALITIES.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
LATONYA STANDIFER: WHEN I WENT
 TO IMMIGRATION AND ASKED

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
FOR MY PAPERWORK
IN ORDER TO GET A WORKING VISA,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
I WAS VERY CONFIDENT.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
FIRST, YOU GOTTA
COME AT 'EM VERY CONFIDENT,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
KNOWING WHAT
YOU'RE TALKING ABOUT, YOU KNOW.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
IT'S JUST FORMS TO BEGIN WITH.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
NARRATOR: JAPAN
 IS TRYING TO FIGURE OUT

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
HOW TO OPEN
 ITS LABOR MARKET TO FOREIGNERS,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
WITHOUT APPEARING TO DO SO.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
ELABORATE LICENSING SYSTEMS,

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
SUPPOSEDLY
 TO REGULATE IMMIGRATION,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
ARE ACTUALLY DESIGNED
 TO DISCOURAGE IMMIGRATION.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
[MAN TRANSLATING OIKAWA]
 17 OF THE 27 TYPES OF VISAS

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
ARE OPEN TO FOREIGN NATIONALS
 COMING HERE TO WORK.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
TO WORK IN TOKYO, YOU NEED
 TO HAVE A VISA TO ENTER JAPAN,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
A CERTIFICATE OF ELIGIBILITY,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
WHICH DEMONSTRATES
 THAT YOU HAVE SPECIAL SKILLS,

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
AND A LOCAL SPONSOR
 WITH A FIRM JOB OFFER.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
WELL, FIRST OF ALL,
WHILE YOU'RE HERE,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
YOU HAVE TO GET
YOUR PICTURES, YOUR PORTFOLIOS,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:23.000
YOUR DEMOS TOGETHER.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
YOU HAVE
TO BUILD UP SOMETHING FIRST,

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.000
BEFORE YOU CAN EVEN
GET THE VISA.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
PEOPLE WILL ALWAYS HIRE
A JAPANESE PERSON FIRST CHOICE,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:31.000
SOMEONE WHO'S BILINGUAL,
BICULTURAL,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
RATHER THAN SHIPPING
SOMEBODY IN FROM OVERSEAS.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
BICULTURAL MEANS
 YOU CAN DO BUSINESS

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
BOTH IN A WESTERN WAY,
 AND A JAPANESE WAY,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
SO YOU CAN FOLLOW
 THE JAPANESE

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
WAY OF DOING BUSINESS,
 WHICH IS TIME-CONSUMING.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
THERE'S A LOT OF FORMALITIES
 YOU HAVE TO FOLLOW,

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:51.000
WHEREAS THE WESTERN WAY,
WE SORT OF--

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
OUR DECISION MAKING'S
VERY QUICK.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
JULIET ROWAN:
 LIKE IN MY OFFICE,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
THEY DON'T LIKE IT
 WHEN WE HAVE IDEAS

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.000
ABOUT PERHAPS
HOW TO CHANGE SOMETHING,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
BECAUSE WE'RE ENCROACHING
ON THEIR TURF,

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
AND PUTTING OUR SET OF VALUES
ONTO THEM. AND I UNDERSTAND.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
SO THAT CAN BE
 REALLY FRUSTRATING,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.000
BECAUSE THAT'S
 THE COMPLETE OPPOSITE OF OUR--

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
MY WESTERN UPBRINGING,
 OR IDEALS.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
AND SO, FOR ME, THAT'S THE
SINGLE MOST FRUSTRATING THING.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
YOU NEVER FEEL LIKE YOU'RE GIVEN
ENOUGH CHANCE TO GO PLACES.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:34.000
RICHARD AGUEBOR:
 I'VE BEEN LIVING HERE

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
FOR ABOUT TEN YEARS.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
I'M GETTING USED TO
 THE JAPANESE WAYS OF THINKING,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
I'M GETTING
 USED TO THE TRADITION,

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.000
THE JAPANESE CULTURE.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.000
THEY HAVE A SYSTEM, YOU KNOW,
A SYSTEM THAT, A PROGRAM SYSTEM,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
LIKE, THEY HAVE
A PARTICULAR BELIEF, YOU KNOW.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.000
THEY BELIEVE IN SETTING WAYS,
"THIS IS HOW IT OUGHT TO BE."

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
AND EVERYBODY SEEMS TO BE
MOVING ALONG THAT DIRECTION.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:58.000
CHIHARU KAWAI:
 I LIVED IN THE STATES

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
FOR MORE THAN EIGHT YEARS,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
EIGHT CONSECUTIVE YEARS,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
AND IT WAS VERY DIFFICULT
 FOR ME TO ADJUST MYSELF

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
BACK TO MY OWN SOCIETY.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
AND, OF COURSE, YOU KNOW,
TO BE VERY HONEST,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
IT'S VERY DIFFICULT FOR A PERSON
LIKE ME TO READJUST MYSELF,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
IN JAPANESE BUSINESS WORLD,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.000
BECAUSE THE VALUES
 ARE DIFFERENT.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING NOMURA]
 I BELIEVE THERE ARE PROFOUND

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
PHILOSOPHICAL DIFFERENCES
 BETWEEN THE WEST AND THE EAST,

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
AND THIS IS WHY WE HAVE
 DIFFERENT VALUE SYSTEMS.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
ACCORDING
 TO WESTERN PHILOSOPHY,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
THE ROLE OF NATURE
 IS TO SATISFY HUMAN NEEDS,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
WHILE IN EASTERN PHILOSOPHY,

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
NATURE AND HUMAN BEINGS
 CAN COEXIST IN HARMONY,

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
AND AS A RESULT
 OF THIS DIFFERENCE,

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
WESTERN AND EASTERN THINKING
 ARE COMPLETELY DIFFERENT.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:58.000
NARRATOR:
 JAPANESE INTELLECTUALS

00:07:58.000 --> 00:07:59.000
AND CORPORATE EXECUTIVES

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
OFTEN SPEAK OF A JAPANESE MODEL

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
DIFFERENT FROM
 THE IDEOLOGICAL FOUNDATIONS

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.000
OF WESTERN CAPITALISM.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
BUT GLOBALIZATION IS PRODUCING

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
A RAPID AWAKENING TO THE FACT
 THAT GLOBAL ENGAGEMENT

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.000
AND INTERDEPENDENCY
 ARE A FACT OF LIFE.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:19.000
THEY'RE NOT SOMETHING JAPAN CAN
 CHOOSE TO BE FOR OR AGAINST.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
EISENACH:
 THE JAPANESE SOCIETY,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
ALSO CERTAINLY THE INDUSTRY,

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
NEEDS TO ADJUST
TO GLOBAL COMPETITION.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
AND THAT ONLY ALLOWS
TO A CERTAIN EXTENT,

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
UP TO A CERTAIN LEVEL,
TO MAINTAIN THEIR OWN WAYS.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
BUT BIG COMPANIES
COMPETE GLOBALLY.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:38.000
THAT CHANGE IS NECESSARY.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
IT'S ALREADY HAPPENING.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
YOU MENTIONED THAT
 YOU HAD ALREADY INTERVIEWED

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
WITH THE PRESIDENT OF NISSAN,

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
WHO IS CLEARLY A NON-JAPANESE,
 AND IS RUNNING

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
THE THIRD-LARGEST
 CAR MANUFACTURER IN JAPAN.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
CORPORATE JAPAN HAS BEEN

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
EXTREMELY DISCREET
AT THE BEGINNING, VERY DISCREET.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
THE PUBLIC WAS VERY CURIOUS.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
WELL, I STARTED TO FEEL
 SOME KIND OF DOUBT,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.000
OR SKEPTICISM,
 AND EVEN SOME CRITICISM,

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
ABOUT CHALLENGING SOME
TRADITIONAL WAY OF DOING THINGS

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
IN JAPAN.
IT NEVER WENT VERY FAR.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
BUT IT EXISTED IN THE MEDIA,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
AND IN, TOO, SOME COMMENTS
MADE BY CEO OF OTHER COMPANIES.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
[MAN TRANSLATING NASHIMOTO]
 HONDA HAS ALWAYS DONE THINGS

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
ITS OWN WAY, AND, UNLIKE
 OTHER JAPANESE COMPANIES

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
LIKE NISSAN, FOR EXAMPLE,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
WE WOULD NEVER LOOK
 FOR OUTSIDERS TO HELP US OUT.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
HONDA WOULD NEVER DO THIS.
 WE WILL ALWAYS GO OUR OWN WAY.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
NARRATOR: CORPORATE JAPAN
 REPRESENTS THE RIGIDITY

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
OF BUSINESS LIFE IN JAPAN,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
AN ENVIRONMENT WHERE PEOPLE ARE
 EXPECTED TO FIT INTO A MOLD,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:49.000
AND WHERE EVERYBODY MUST
 FIT PERFECTLY INTO THE SPACE

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.000
ASSIGNED TO HIM OR HER
 BY THE CORPORATION.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
BUT NOW, IN TOKYO,
 THE NEW GENERATION

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
IS EAGER TO TAKE ITS CHANCES
 OUTSIDE THE CORPORATE FOLD.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
[MAN TRANSLATING TAKANIRO]
 MY FATHER WORKS FOR A BIG

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
CORPORATION, BUT I DON'T WANT
 TO CLIMB THE CORPORATE LADDER,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
BECAUSE THERE'S ALWAYS A LIMIT
 ON HOW HIGH YOU CAN GO.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
I DON'T WANT A LIFE LIKE THAT.
 I WANT TO BE MYSELF,

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
AND NOT JUST A NUMBER
 IN A BIG CORPORATION.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
THAT'S WHY I'M A MUSICIAN.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
KANAK: THE YOUNG PEOPLE
 AREN'T CHARGING IN

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
TO HAVING
 THESE LIFETIME CAREERS

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
IN MAJOR ORGANIZATIONS
UNTHINKINGLY.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
THEY'RE THINKING ABOUT
WHERE THEY WANT TO WORK.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
AND THERE'S A LOT
OF YOUNG PEOPLE TODAY

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.000
THAT ARE LOOKING TO BE FREE.
THEY WANT TO DO PART-TIME JOBS,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
THEY WANT
TO BE ABLE TO MOVE AROUND.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.000
I THINK
THAT'S A FUNDAMENTAL CHANGE.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
[MAN TRANSLATING]
 I WOULD LIKE TO BE MYSELF

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:46.000
AND DO WHAT I REALLY WANT,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
BUT JAPANESE SOCIETY
 DOESN'T ALLOW ME.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING]
 I DON'T DRESS LIKE THIS

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:56.000
TO SEND
 PROTEST MESSAGES TO PEOPLE.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I JUST LIKE IT, SO I DO IT.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
[MAN TRANSLATING]
 IN TOKYO, YOU HAVE THE FREEDOM

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
TO BE WHATEVER YOU WANT TO BE.
 AND I AM.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
NARRATOR: "YOUNG JAPANESE
 THINK THEY CAN BE ANYTHING,"

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.000
SAYS YU MIRI. "THEY THINK
 FREEDOM IS SOMETHING SIMPLE,

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
"BUT THEY DON'T UNDERSTAND
 WHAT THAT WORD REALLY MEANS."

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
[SPEAKING JAPANESE]

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
NARRATOR:
 YU MIRI IS ONE OF JAPAN'S

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
MOST POPULAR WRITERS.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
HER NOVELS HAVE ATTRACTED
 A PASSIONATE FOLLOWING,

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
ESPECIALLY AMONG YOUNG WOMEN.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
YU MIRI'S BREAKTHROUGH
 CAME IN 1999, WHEN HER BOOK,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.000
"KAZUKU CINEMA (FAMILY CINEMA)"
 WON THE AKUTAWA PRIZE,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
ONE OF JAPAN'S MOST PRESTIGIOUS
 LITERARY AWARDS.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
BEYOND THE ATTENTION
 HER BOOKS RECEIVED,

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
SHE BECAME A CELEBRITY
 AS A FOCUS OF RACIST RAGE.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
RIGHT-WINGERS THREATENED
 TO BURN BOOKSTORES,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
AND MANY EVENTS
 HAD TO BE CANCELLED.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
OF KOREAN DESCENT,
 YU MIRI'S STORY

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
PERSONIFIES THE MISTREATMENT
 OF JAPAN'S LARGEST MINORITY.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING MIRI]
 AS A SECOND-GENERATION

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
KOREAN JAPANESE, I HAVE
 PROBLEMS AT HOME AND AT SCHOOL.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.000
AT HOME, I COULD NOT
 UNDERSTAND KOREAN,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
AND I DIDN'T WANT TO LEARN IT.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
THIS MADE
 MY KOREAN PARENTS ANGRY.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
AT SCHOOL, I WAS ABUSED
 BECAUSE, AS A KOREAN,

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
MY CLASSMATES AND TEACHERS
 CONSIDERED ME INFERIOR.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
NARRATOR: THE LARGEST
 INFLUX OF FOREIGNERS

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:21.000
IN JAPAN'S HISTORY

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.000
WAS THE ARRIVAL
 OF THOUSANDS OF KOREANS,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.000
FORCIBLY BROUGHT TO JAPAN
 TO WORK OR FIGHT ON ITS BEHALF

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
IN THE LATE 1930s,
 RIGHT BEFORE WORLD WAR II.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
TODAY, ALMOST HALF A MILLION
 KOREANS LIVE IN TOKYO,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
AND AFTER SEVERAL GENERATIONS,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
THEY'RE STILL CLASSIFIED
 AS FOREIGNERS.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
WATTS: THE WAY IT CHARACTERIZES
 "JAPANESENESS"

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.000
IS NOT ABOUT WHO'S BORN HERE.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
IT'S ABOUT HAVING BLOOD
THAT STRETCHES BACK

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:49.000
OVER A CERTAIN PERIOD OF TIME.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
WHEREAS,
FOR EXAMPLE, IN THE U.K.,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
YOUR NATIONALITY'S DETERMINED
BY WHERE YOU WERE BORN,

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.000
WHEREAS IN JAPAN,
YOUR NATIONALITY IS DETERMINED

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
BY WHO
 YOUR FATHER AND MOTHER WAS.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING LEE]
 I HAVEN'T CONFRONTED

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
DISCRIMINATION DIRECTLY,
 BUT I THINK THE REASON IS

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
THAT I MARRIED A EUROPEAN MAN,
 A GERMAN, AND I SPEAK GERMAN,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
SO PEOPLE HERE IN TOKYO SEE ME
 AS HALF ASIAN AND HALF GERMAN,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
AND THEY TREAT ME DIFFERENTLY
 THAN OTHER ASIANS.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
BUT OTHER KOREANS
 FACE DISCRIMINATION EVERY DAY,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.000
ESPECIALLY
 IN THEIR NEIGHBORHOODS.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
AND EVEN WHEN
 THEY CHANGE THEIR KOREAN NAMES

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
TO A JAPANESE NAME,
 AND WANT TO PASS AS JAPANESE,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
PEOPLE OF KOREAN DESCENT
 ARE STILL CONSIDERED OUTSIDERS.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
NARRATOR: THIRD AND FOURTH
 GENERATION KOREAN JAPANESE,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
WHO PASS AS JAPANESE,
 YET ARE DENIED CITIZENSHIP,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
MAINTAIN THAT IN TOKYO,
 BLOOD ALONE DEFINES IDENTITY.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
MORE RECENT NEWCOMERS, HOWEVER,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
FEEL WELL-INTEGRATED
 IN JAPANESE SOCIETY,

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
AND BELIEVE THAT SHARED VALUES
 AND MUTUAL SELF-INTEREST

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
ARE BEGINNING
 TO DEFINE JAPANESE IDENTITY.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
[SOFT ROCK SINGING]

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
AGUEBOR: THESE PEOPLE,
 THEY REALLY ARE SET PEOPLE.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
THEY ARE SET HERE.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
THEY TAKE YOU, YOU BECOME
 PART AND PARCEL OF THEM,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
ESPECIALLY WHEN YOU'RE GETTING
MORE INVOLVED WITH THEM,

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
WHEN YOU COME
 TO UNDERSTAND THEIR WAYS.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
SO YOU ARE FULLY ACCEPTED.
THEY TAKE YOU AS ONE OF THEM.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
IT'S NOT AS DISCRIMINATORY
AS MOST PEOPLE THINK.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
IT'S NOT AT ALL.
THEY HAVE ACCEPTED ME.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
AND I THINK IF THEY CAN
ACCEPT ME AS A BLACK MAN,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
THEY CAN ACCEPT ANY OTHER
PERSON, ALL OVER THE WORLD.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
BLACK FRIENDS I'VE HAD,
WHO'VE COME FROM THE U.K.,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
OR COME FROM THE U.S.,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
HAVE EXPERIENCED
A DIFFERENT JAPAN.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
ONE CANADIAN GUY I KNEW
WHO'S A BLACK GUY,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
HE WANTED
 TO FIND ACCOMMODATION,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
AND HE ORGANIZED EVERYTHING
 OVER THE TELEPHONE,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
AND HAD IT ALL SET UP,
 IT WAS AGREED HE'D MOVE IN.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
AND THEN WHEN HE ARRIVED
AND THEY SAW HE WAS BLACK,

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
RATHER THAN HEARING
JUST A CANADIAN VOICE,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
HE WAS-- SUDDENLY
THAT FLAT WAS NOT AVAILABLE.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
[MAN TRANSLATING KAMPPETER]
 AS A EUROPEAN, A GERMAN,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
I SENSE THAT I'M ACCEPTED

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
A LITTLE BIT MORE
 THAN OTHER FOREIGNERS.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.000
BUT JAPANESE PEOPLE STILL DON'T
 WANT TO GET TOO CLOSE TO ME.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
THEY KEEP THEIR DISTANCE.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
AS FAR AS RELATING
WITH THE JAPANESE PEOPLE,

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.000
I HAVEN'T HAD SO MANY PROBLEMS.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
SOMETIMES I THINK
THEY'RE A LITTLE SCARED OF ME,

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
BECAUSE I'M A BIT LOUD
COMPARED TO THEM, BUT...

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
[LAUGHS]

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
MOST OF THE TIME, IT'S OK.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
NARRATOR: THE JAPANESE
 ARE DEEPLY PRIVATE PEOPLE.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
THEY LIVE IN
 A PROTOCOL-CONSTRICTED SOCIETY

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
WHERE VENTURING
 ONE'S OPINION, TOO FORCIBLY,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.000
OR EVEN OUT OF TURN,
 IS FROWNED UPON.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
THESE ARE
 HIGHLY CIVILIZED PEOPLE,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
MEMBERS OF A SOCIETY
 SO ORDERED AS TO SEEM ALIEN.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
TOKYO IS UNQUESTIONABLY
 A MODERN CITY,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:49.000
BUT CERTAIN TRADITIONAL CUSTOMS
 HAVE NOT CHANGED FOR CENTURIES.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[CHANTING IN JAPANESE]

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
[MAN TRANSLATING OKUYAMA]
 I HELP SICK PEOPLE

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
WHO ARE SUFFERING FROM PHYSICAL
 OR EMOTIONAL PROBLEMS.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
MANY OF MY PATIENTS
 HAVE GONE TO REGULAR DOCTORS,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
BUT THEY HAVE NOT
 GOTTEN BETTER,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:09.000
BECAUSE MOST OF THEIR PROBLEMS
 ARE CAUSED BY THE SPIRITS,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
WHICH LIVE INSIDE
 OUR MINDS AND BODIES,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
AND DOCTORS DON'T KNOW
 HOW TO DEAL WITH THE SPIRITS.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
NARRATOR:
 JAPANESE ZEN BUDDHISM

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:21.000
BELIEVES IN THE GREAT,
 LIBERATING SPIRIT,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
A SPIRITUAL FORCE
 WHICH CAN HELP BELIEVERS

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
LIBERATE THEMSELVES
 FROM THE DOMINANCE OF GREED,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
AND FROM THE SHACKLES
 OF ILLUSIONS.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
TO MANY OUTSIDERS,
 TOKYO PRESENTS THE IMAGE

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
OF A CITY TOO HAMSTRUNG
 BY ITS OWN CULTURAL TRADITIONS

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.000
TO FULLY EMBRACE
 GLOBALIZATION.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
YET THE AVERAGE TOKYOITE
 GETS A BIG KICK OUT OF GOING

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
TO AN AMERICAN-STYLE
 BASEBALL GAME,

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
JAPAN'S NATIONAL SPORT,
 AND THEN HAVING A FAST MEAL

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
AT ONE OF THE
 KENTUCKY FRIED CHICKEN STORES

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
INSIDE THE TOKYO DOME.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
KANAK:
 IT'S NOT SURPRISING

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
THAT THERE'S
A LOT OF AMERICAN ASPECT

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
TO CERTAIN THINGS
THAT GO ON IN JAPAN, I THINK.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
I MEAN, THE TWO COUNTRIES
HAVE FORMED SO MANY BONDS

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
OVER SUCH
A LONG PERIOD OF TIME.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
NARRATOR: AND FEW
 AMERICAN-JAPANESE BONDS

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.000
ARE AS STRONG
 AS McDONALD'S HAMBURGERS.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
THE FIRST STORE
 OPENED IN TOKYO IN 1971.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.000
TODAY, OVER 300 STORES
 ARE OPERATING IN TOKYO,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
AND McDONALD'S JAPAN
 HAS ANNUAL SALES

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:36.000
OF $3.4 BILLION, SECOND ONLY
 TO THE UNITED STATES.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
[MAN TRANSLATING KENJI KANIYA]
 JAPANESE LIKE THE TASTE

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:47.000
OF KETCHUP, BUT THEY ALSO LIKE
SOY SAUCE AND GINGER TASTES,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
SO McDONALD'S TRIES
TO OFFER ITS CUSTOMERS

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
ALL OF THESE FLAVORS.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
THAT'S WHY WE'VE INTRODUCED
 PRODUCTS UNIQUE TO JAPAN,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
LIKE OUR CHICKEN TASTA,
 AND OUR TERIYAKI BURGERS.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
McDONALD'S IS FULLY OPERATED
 BY JAPANESE STAFF,

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
BECAUSE THESE ARE PEOPLE
 WHO UNDERSTAND AND RELATE

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.000
TO THE CULTURE OF THE CUSTOMERS
 THAT THEY'RE SERVING.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
AND FOR US,
 THIS IS VERY IMPORTANT.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
NARRATOR:
 AT McDONALD'S JAPAN,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
MEETING THE DEMANDS
 OF LOCAL CULTURE

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:16.000
MEANS ADOPTING JAPANESE
 MARKETING STRATEGIES.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.000
IN TOKYO, FOR INSTANCE,

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
McDONALD'S IS CALLED
 "MAKUDONARUDO,"

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
A SOUND THAT IS MORE PLEASANT
 TO JAPANESE EARS.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:29.000
CHANGE, AMID NO CHANGE,
 IS AN OLD JAPANESE STORY.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
SO IS ACCOMMODATING
 TO THINGS FOREIGN.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
LET THE FOREIGNERS IN,
 SO AS TO KEEP THEM OUT,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
IS THE PRINCIPLE.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
ACCEPT
 THOSE PRACTICES FROM ABROAD

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
THAT DO NOT
 THREATEN THE FUNDAMENTALS.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
ROWAN: YOU ALWAYS
 REMAIN AN OUTSIDER.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
I HATE TO SAY IT,
BUT YOU DO, BECAUSE...

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
BECAUSE YOU'RE NOT JAPANESE,
FOR THAT SIMPLE REASON.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
SO, FOR THAT REASON,
I DON'T THINK

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
I WANT TO SPEND
MY WHOLE LIFE HERE,

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
BECAUSE I DON'T FEEL
 LIKE I COULD BE

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.000
INTEGRATED ENOUGH
 INTO THE SOCIETY

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
TO WANT TO STAY HERE FOREVER.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
I DON'T FEEL
CLOSE ENOUGH TO PEOPLE.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.000
I FIND IT VERY, VERY EASY.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:16.000
BUT THAT IS PERHAPS BECAUSE
I HAVEN'T TRIED TO BE JAPANESE.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
I LIVE AS A...
I LIVE AS A FOREIGNER, AND I...

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:25.000
I HAVE A JAPANESE WIFE,
AND WE HAVE TWO KIDS,

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
WHO ARE OBVIOUSLY
 HALF AND HALF.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
WE HAVEN'T EXPERIENCED
ANY REAL PROBLEMS.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
[AMERICAN ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING LEE] I WOULD
 SAY THAT A MIXED MARRIAGE,

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.000
AN INTERNATIONAL MARRIAGE,
 MAKES LIFE MORE INTERESTING,

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
AND IT'S
 AN ENRICHING EXPERIENCE.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
BUT IT'S NOT ALWAYS EASY

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
TO LIVE IN A MIXED MARRIAGE,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
BECAUSE YOU HAVE
 TWO DIFFERENT CULTURES,

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
EITHER COMING TOGETHER,
 OR CLASHING WITH EACH OTHER.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
[MAN TRANSLATING KAMPPETER]
 IN TOKYO, A FEW YEARS AGO,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
IT WAS DIFFICULT
 TO BE IN A MIXED MARRIAGE,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
BUT NOW THERE'S NO PROBLEM

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.000
FOR JAPANESE AND EUROPEAN
 COUPLES. IT'S ACCEPTED.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.000
BUT MIXED MARRIAGES BETWEEN
 JAPANESE AND NON-EUROPEANS

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
ARE NOT YET ACCEPTED.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
[LATIN SALSA MUSIC PLAYING]

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING ISHIGAWA]
 MY PARENTS OPPOSED MY MARRIAGE,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
NOT BECAUSE MY FIANCE
 WAS A LATINO,

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:28.000
BUT BECAUSE,
 LIKE MOST JAPANESE PARENTS,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
THEY DON'T WANT THEIR CHILDREN
 TO MARRY FOREIGNERS.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
[MAN TRANSLATING KUBO]
 I THINK IT WAS EASY FOR ME

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.000
TO MARRY YOKO,
 BECAUSE SHE SPEAKS SPANISH.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:42.000
I'M SURE IT WOULD HAVE BEEN
 MORE DIFFICULT

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:45.000
TO MARRY A WOMAN
 WHO SPEAKS ONLY JAPANESE.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.000
WE BOTH ALSO LOVE
 TO DANCE SALSA. THAT HELPED.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
BUT WE STILL HAVE
 LOTS OF PROBLEMS.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
[WOMAN TRANSLATING ISHIGAWA]
 WHAT I DISCOVERED

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.000
IN MY MARRIAGE
 IS THAT LOVEMAKING

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:59.000
IS THE SAME, NO MATTER
 WHERE YOU COME FROM.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
LATINO OR JAPANESE,
 IT'S ALL THE SAME.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
IT ALL DEPENDS ON THE LOVER.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.000
[MAN TRANSLATING KUBO] 
 WHEN A JAPANESE WOMAN

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:09.000
ENTERS THE SALSA WORLD,
 HER PERSONALITY CHANGES.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:10.000
SHE MEETS LOTS OF LATINOS,

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.000
AND QUICKLY SHE LEARNS
 HOW TO DEAL WITH THEM,

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:17.000
WHAT TO DO
 AND WHAT NOT TO DO, YOU KNOW?

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
BUT EVEN WHEN A JAPANESE WOMAN
 LOVES SALSA AND SPEAKS SPANISH,

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:24.000
IT'S NOT EASY.
 THERE ARE BIG DIFFERENCES

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.000
BETWEEN BEING LATINO
 AND BEING JAPANESE.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
BIG DIFFERENCES.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:32.000
I CAN TEACH THE JAPANESE
 TO DANCE SALSA,

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
BUT I CANNOT TEACH THEM

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:35.000
THE FEELING THAT YOU NEED
 TO DANCE WELL.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:40.000
THAT'S VERY DIFFICULT TO TEACH.
 IT COMES OUT NATURALLY.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.000
AND THE JAPANESE HAVE PROBLEMS
 EXPRESSING FEELING.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
THEY DO IT,
 THEY DO EXPRESS FEELING.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.000
BUT IT'S DIFFERENT.
 IT'S THEIR OWN KIND OF FEELING.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:54.000
[SALSA MUSIC PLAYING]

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.000
NARRATOR:
 DESPITE THE MANY PROBLEMS

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:57.000
FACED BY
 FOREIGNERS LIVING IN TOKYO,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:00.000
THOUSANDS OF PEOPLE
 FROM ALL OVER THE WORLD

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.000
ARE COMING TO TOKYO,
 LOOKING FOR ADVENTURE,

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:07.000
OR NEW OPPORTUNITIES.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:09.000
KRUMPLITSCH: TO A YOUNG WOMAN
 WANTING TO MOVE TO TOKYO,

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:13.000
I WOULD SAY,
 GO FOR IT. DON'T BE SCARED.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
IT'S A GREAT COUNTRY
 TO LIVE IN,

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:16.000
ESPECIALLY
 AS A YOUNG WOMAN HERE.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
IT'S VERY SAFE.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
I CAN WALK AROUND ANYWHERE,
IN THE MIDDLE OF THE NIGHT,

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:23.000
AND NOT FEEL LIKE I'M GONNA
GET ATTACKED, OR ANYTHING.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:29.000
NARRATOR: PERHAPS
 THE MOST SHOCKING ASPECT

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:31.000
OF EVERYDAY LIFE IN TOKYO
 FOR NEWCOMERS ARE THE CROWDS.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
WHEREVER YOU GO IN THE CITY,
 YOU'RE CONFRONTED

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
BY HUGE WAVES OF PEOPLE.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:43.000
ROWAN:
 WHEN I FIRST ARRIVED IN JAPAN,

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.000
I USED TO GET REALLY
 FREAKED OUT ABOUT PEOPLE.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
I FELT LIKE THEY WERE
 INVADING MY PERSONAL SPACE.

